                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1238">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/4322.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-28T18:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 28, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President stated to me to-day that the Federal army would exercise the
                    greatest care if an attack on Ciudad Juárez became necessary to avoid firing
                    across the line, but hoped that our Government would cooperate in every way
                    possible to terminate an abnormal situation, which must result from Federal
                    inability to attack effectually. He added an expression of his deep appreciation
                    of the friendship and patience which the President has displayed toward Mexico
                    throughout the recent trying times.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
